<h2>HVAC Systems for Raleigh</h2>
<p>Raleigh's Hot-Humid climate demands HVAC systems specifically designed to handle both high temperatures and moisture management. The ideal system for Raleigh homes should feature a minimum SEER rating of 16, though SEER 18-20 systems provide better long-term value given the extended cooling season and Duke Energy's electricity rates. Heat pumps are particularly effective in Raleigh's moderate winter climate, providing both efficient heating and cooling while maintaining lower operating costs than traditional split systems.</p>

<p>Variable-speed air handlers and two-stage compressors offer superior humidity control, crucial for Raleigh's climate where indoor humidity levels can quickly become uncomfortable without proper equipment. For the average 2,050 square foot home, a 3-4 ton system typically provides adequate capacity, though proper load calculations should always be performed. Ductless mini-split systems are gaining popularity in Raleigh for their zoned comfort control and high efficiency ratings, often achieving SEER ratings above 20 while providing precise temperature and humidity management.</p>

<h2>Raleigh Energy Incentives</h2>
<p>Raleigh residents benefit from several attractive incentives for solar and energy-efficient HVAC systems. The federal solar Investment Tax Credit (ITC) provides a 30% credit for solar installations through 2032, before stepping down to 26% in 2033 and 22% in 2034. This credit applies to the total system cost including equipment, installation, and interconnection fees, making it one of the most valuable renewable energy incentives available.</p>

<p>While North Carolina discontinued its state tax credit for residential solar in 2015, Duke Energy offers rebates for energy-efficient equipment through their Smart Saver program. Heat pump rebates range from \$300-600 depending on efficiency levels, while high-efficiency central air systems can qualify for rebates up to \$350. Additionally, Duke Energy's net metering program allows solar customers to receive credit for excess power fed back to the grid, though compensation is provided at the utility's avoided cost rate rather than retail rates. Property tax exemptions for solar installations ensure that adding solar panels won't increase property tax assessments, preserving long-term affordability.</p>

